%N A389488 Total sum of the lengths of the first runs in heapable permutations of length n.
%C A389488 A permutation of [1..n] is heapable if it can be inserted, one element at a time, into a binary min-heap without violating the heap property.
%C A389488 The first run (or initial increasing segment) of a permutation is the maximal prefix that is strictly increasing: p1 < p2 < ... < pk.
%C A389488 The length of the first run is k.
%H A389488 Benjamin Chen, Michael Cho, Mario Tutuncu-Macias, and Tony Tzolov, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.dam.2023.01.025">Efficient methods of calculating the number of heapable permutations</a>, Discrete Applied Mathematics Volume 331, 31 May 2023, Pages 126-137.
%H A389488 Manolopoulos Panagiotis, <a href="/A389488/a389488.py.txt">Python program</a>
%e A389488 For n=4, the heapable permutations are: (1,2,3,4), (1,3,2,4), (1,2,4,3), (1,4,2,3), (1,3,4,2).
%e A389488 Lengths of first runs:
%e A389488   (1,2,3,4): run 1,2,3,4 length 4.
%e A389488   (1,3,2,4): run 1,3 length 2.
%e A389488   (1,2,4,3): run 1,2,4 length 3.
%e A389488   (1,4,2,3): run 1,4 length 2.
%e A389488   (1,3,4,2): run 1,3,4 length 3.
%e A389488 So among the 5 heapable permutations of length 4:
%e A389488   1 permutation has first run of length 4,
%e A389488   2 permutations have first run of length 3,
%e A389488   2 permutations have first run of length 2,
%e A389488 for a total of 14.
